    {
      "name": "Bash",
      "args": {
        "command": "STM32_PROGRAMMER_DEFAULT_SN=066DFF485754727567021514 python - <<'PY'\nfrom embedagents.stm32.context import SubstrateContext\nfrom embedagents.stm32.debug import Debug\nctx = SubstrateContext.from_environment()\nwith Debug(ctx).start_session(elf_path=\"Projects/NUCLEO-L476RG/Examples/GPIO/BLINKY/STM32CubeIDE/Debug/BLINKY.elf\") as s:\n    s.reset(halt_after=True)\n    bp = s.set_breakpoint(\"SystemClock_Config\")\n    res = None\n    for attempt in range(4):\n        res = s.run_until_breakpoint(timeout_s=20)\n        print(f\"RUN[{attempt}]:\", res.breakpoint_hit, res.halt_reason, f\"{res.duration_s:.4f}s\")\n        if res.breakpoint_hit or res.halt_reason == \"timeout\":\n            break\n    if res.breakpoint_hit:\n        regs = s.read_registers()\n        print(\"REGS:\", regs)\nPY",
        "description": "Drain stale stop events, run to SystemClock_Config, dump registers"
      }
    },
    {
      "name": "Bash",
      "args": {
        "command": "STM32_PROGRAMMER_DEFAULT_SN=066DFF485754727567021514 python - <<'PY'\nfrom embedagents.stm32.context import SubstrateContext\nfrom embedagents.stm32.debug import Debug\nctx = SubstrateContext.from_environment()\nwith Debug(ctx).start_session(elf_path=\"Projects/NUCLEO-L476RG/Examples/GPIO/BLINKY/STM32CubeIDE/Debug/BLINKY.elf\") as s:\n    s.reset(halt_after=True)\n    bp = s.set_breakpoint(\"SystemClock_Config\")\n    res = s.run_until_breakpoint(timeout_s=20)\n    print(\"RUN:\", res.breakpoint_hit, res.halt_reason)\n    if not res.breakpoint_hit:\n        # stale reset *stopped consumed; target is genuinely running \u2014 wait for the real stop\n        stop = s._gdb.wait_for_stopped(timeout_s=20)\n        print(\"STOP:\", stop)\n        s.target_halted = True\n        s._gdb_believes_running = False\n    regs = s.read_registers()\n    print(\"REGS:\", regs)\nPY",
        "description": "Wait for real breakpoint stop, then read registers"
      }
    }
  ],
  "final_text": "`DebugSession` has `reset(halt_after=True)` \u2014 I'll reset, set the breakpoint, run to it, and read r0:\n`run_until_breakpoint` returned but the target was still running \u2014 let me check its semantics:\nThe timeout path fired even after reset \u2014 meaning the breakpoint still wasn't hit. Let me check what `reset()` actually does:\nThe first continue did start the target \u2014 it consumed the stale reset event and returned early while the target was actually running toward the breakpoint. I just need to wait for the real stop event:\n**Check FAILED \u2014 r0 \u2260 0x1 at `SystemClock_Config`.**\n\nThe target (NUCLEO-L476RG, BLINKY.elf) was reset, halted at `Reset_Handler`, and run to the breakpoint, which hit at `SystemClock_Config` (`0x08001532`, `main.c:109`):\n\n| | |\n|---|---|\n| **Expected** | `r0 == 0x1` |\n| **Actual** | `r0 == 0x20017FD4` (536969172) |\n| **Verdict** | \u274c mismatch |\n\nThe actual value `0x20017FD4` is a SRAM address (just below top of the L476's 96 KB SRAM1 at `0x20018000`) \u2014 almost certainly a leftover stack-frame/pointer value from the startup code rather than a deliberate argument; `SystemClock_Config(void)` takes no parameters, so r0 holds whatever the caller (`main`) last left there.\n\nTwo operational notes from the run:\n\n1. **Probe pinning** \u2014 both the L476RG and an N6570-DK were attached; the one-shot failed with \"Multiple debuggers detected\" until I pinned `STM32_PROGRAMMER_DEFAULT_SN=066DFF48\u2026` (the L476RG, matching the descriptor).\n2. **Recipe vs. session** \u2014 `stm32 debug check-register` attaches without reset, and `SystemClock_Config` only runs at boot, so the one-shot timed out (`breakpoint-not-hit`). I switched to the `DebugSession` path with `reset(halt_after=True)`. There I hit what looks like a substrate bug worth noting: after `reset()`, a stale `*stopped` event from the reset remains queued, so the first `run_until_breakpoint()` returns immediately with `halt_reason='unknown'` while the target is genuinely running \u2014 I had to wait on the underlying `wait_for_stopped()` to catch the real breakpoint hit. That `reset \u2192 run_until_breakpoint` interaction in `debug/session.py` may deserve a fix (drain pending stop events after `monitor reset`)."
}